{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"b6d7b6a94863c95536ddf1a2a660ef1494c9d8a91dcda84b4d14696d82dba3fb","slug":"reproducible-research.testing.testing-integrationtest","location":"/reproducible-research/testing/testing-integrationtest.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Integration Testing","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"The Turing Way Community","given":"The Turing Way","family":"Community"},"name":"The Turing Way Community","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true},"code":{"id":"MIT","url":"https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT","name":"MIT License","free":true,"osi":true}},"github":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way","copyright":"2019-2025","numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way/blob/main/book/website/reproducible-research/testing/testing-integrationtest.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"testing-integrationtest.md","url":"/build/testing-integrationt-bb3e6b129287d6e54f1db9ab8fec2c88.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Integration testing is a level of software testing where individual units are combined and tested as a group.\nWhile unit tests validate the functionality of code in isolation, integration tests ensure that components cooperate when interfacing with one another.\nThe purpose of this level of testing is to expose faults in the interaction between integrated units.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"dDmEqYSRPH"}],"key":"znCWf4axeg"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For example, maybe a unit that reads in some data is working and passes its unit tests, and the following unit that cleans up the data once it’s been read in is also working and passes its tests.\nHowever say the first unit outputs the data as (time_data, temperature_data) but the function that cleans the data expects input of the form (temperature_data, time_data).\nThis can obviously lead to bugs.\nWhile the units are correct there in an error in their integration.","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"Nc7yJ9A5Mk"}],"key":"sNcF7QDEf3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"An example of an integration test for this case could be to supply a test data file, use these functions to read it in and clean it, and check the resulting cleaned data against what would be expected.\nIf a bug like this is present then the cleaned data outputted would be very unlikely to match the expected result, and an error would be raised.","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"R6Xd80IFss"}],"key":"OwckCN9hnz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Integration testing is particularly important in collaborative projects where different people work on different parts of the code.\nIf two different people complete separate units and then need to integrate them integration issues are more likely as neither may understand the other’s code.\nA famous example of this is a multi-million dollar satellite which ","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"Q1gFyh7MZa"},{"type":"link","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_Climate_Orbiter","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"crashed","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"MqqRbzsIRb"}],"urlSource":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_Climate_Orbiter","data":{"page":"Mars_Climate_Orbiter","wiki":"https://en.wikipedia.org/","lang":"en"},"internal":false,"protocol":"wiki","key":"tYh0yWlSEO"},{"type":"text","value":" because one piece of code outputted distance data in feet, while another assumed data in meters.\nThis is another example of an integration issue.","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"U0T9O92hvd"}],"key":"gzOxqVFSOi"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A sub-type of integration testing is system integration testing.\nThis tests the integration of systems, packages and any interfaces to external organizations (such as Electronic Data Interchange, Internet).\nDepending on the nature of a project system integration testing may or may not be applicable.","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"key":"s9c8c35bIK"}],"key":"RFwqLoNi3D"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Integration Testing Approaches","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"Ts9cG9595e"}],"identifier":"integration-testing-approaches","label":"Integration Testing Approaches","html_id":"integration-testing-approaches","implicit":true,"key":"tFdLRl34iB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are several different approaches to integration testing.\nBig Bang is an approach to integration testing where all or most of the units are combined together and tested at one go.\nThis approach is taken when the testing team receives the entire software in a bundle.\nSo what is the difference between Big Bang integration testing and system testing? Well, the former tests only the interactions between the units while the latter tests the entire system.","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"HdXcuXueri"}],"key":"rbeubgkcEX"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Top Down is an approach to integration testing where top-level sections of the code (that themselves contain many smaller units) are tested first and lower level units are tested step by step after that.\nSo is a code can be split into the main steps A, B, and C, and each of those contain steps to complete them, and these steps may have substeps like:","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"key":"lSLiI39iF0"}],"key":"MA1q0gGrlE"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"v2nw9aKbyg"}],"key":"CoUOW5gdUY"}],"key":"BFc3avEFtg"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A.1","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":36,"column":1}},"key":"QuIBSSA6I9"}],"key":"aNfAVLCHYv"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":37,"column":1},"end":{"line":37,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A.1.1","position":{"star